## 6. Versioning and evolution of module contracts

**Yes — adopt lightweight semantic versioning per module contract, not per the whole architecture document.**

Given this project's structure (freeze module, move to next, revisit rarely), a full architecture-wide version number is too coarse — it would force a version bump even when only one module's contract changes. Instead:

- **Each module's output contract gets its own version** (e.g., `SelectionResult v1`). Additive changes (new optional field) can stay within the same major version. Any change that removes a field, changes a field's meaning, or changes a Status enum's values is a breaking change and requires a major version bump.
- **Downstream modules declare which contract version they were built against** (a comment/constant is sufficient in Pine — this doesn't need tooling). This makes it trivial, months later, to answer "did Pool Selection's contract change since Entry Engine was built against it?" without re-reading every line of both modules.
- **The architecture document itself should carry a document version** (you're effectively already doing this — "v2" after the Configuration/Priority additions) so you can tell, at a glance, whether a given frozen module was implemented against the current or an older version of its design doc.

This is intentionally lightweight — no need for formal semver tooling or automated compatibility checking in a Pine Script project. The value is purely in the discipline of **writing the version number down**, so "did this change break anything downstream" becomes a quick lookup instead of a full re-audit.

