## THE FINAL AUDIT — Full System, Hidden Coupling and Expensive-to-Change Risk

Synthesizing this session and the prior one into a single, final list — ranked by cost-if-deferred, restricted only to items that are genuinely expensive to fix after Phase 5 freeze:

| Rank | Risk | Why it's expensive later | Action before freeze |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | **Registry schema gaps** (pool type, symbol/timeframe, stable Pool ID scheme) | Every module reads Registry directly; a schema change ripples through the entire system at once | Finalize the essential field list (Q2) now; treat as Tier 1 frozen once set |
| 2 | **Execution State ownership undecided** | If bolted onto Lifecycle or Trade Manager by default, unwinding later means reopening a Tier 1/2 module | Commit to a dedicated Execution State module now (contract only; implementation can wait) |
| 3 | **No formal Result-object standard applied uniformly** | Debug Dashboard, failure propagation, and testing all silently depend on this being consistent; retrofitting it to 7 already-built modules is real work | Apply the standard retroactively as thin wrappers now, before more modules are added on top |
| 4 | **No explicit fail-closed rule at the Alerts/MT5 boundary** | This is the one gap with direct financial consequence — a silent fallback here is the worst possible failure mode | Write the "Integrity=false ⇒ no alert, no order, no exception" rule into the architecture document explicitly, before Alerts/MT5 are built |
| 5 | **Execution-order/bar-confirmation invariant not yet documented** | Subtle correctness bug, easy to introduce, hard to trace once several more modules stack on top | Document and verify now |
| 6 | **Contract versioning not yet adopted** | Costs little now; becomes expensive to reconstruct retroactively once contracts have already changed a few times unversioned | Start version-tagging output contracts starting with Pool Selection, going forward |

**Everything else — sequential pipeline shape, thin event layer for notifications only, ranked-list Pool Selection output, strict downstream-ignorance between modules, Registry-as-sole-source-of-truth — is correctly decided and should not change.** These are exactly the decisions that are cheap to get right early and expensive to revisit, and you've already gotten them right.

**Bottom line for this audit:** the architecture doesn't need a structural redesign. What it needs, before Phase 5 is truly frozen, is for six specific cross-cutting agreements (table above) to be **written down as explicit, permanent rules** rather than left as implicit conventions — because the cost of formalizing them now is a few paragraphs of documentation, and the cost of discovering the gap later is reopening modules you've already committed to treating as finished.
